{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"87b3e475-2ec5-451c-a079-349b24fcd0bd","content":"For NativeAOT, the runtime won't auto-discover `createdump` — you must explicitly point to it via `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`. Here's the full configuration:\n\n**Environment variables** (on your container):\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  # Enable crash dump generation\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  # Full heap dump (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"\n  # Required for NativeAOT — runtime won't find createdump on its own\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n  # Dump output path (%d=PID, %t=timestamp)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%d\"\n```\n\n**Pod spec changes:**\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: your-app\n      # ... existing config ...\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add:\n            # createdump needs ptrace to read process memory\n            - SYS_PTRACE\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: dump-volume\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: dump-volume\n      emptyDir:\n        # Set a size limit so a runaway dump doesn't fill the node\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** is the critical one for NativeAOT — without it the runtime has no way to locate `createdump` and dumps silently won't be generated.\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** is required because `createdump` uses `ptrace` to snapshot the process.\n- Use `emptyDir` with a `sizeLimit` to avoid filling the node disk on repeated crashes.\n- To debug dump creation issues, add `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics=1` — it logs createdump's own stderr.\n- Dumps in `emptyDir` are lost on pod restart; if you need persistence, swap it for a `PersistentVolumeClaim`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aa94418b-684b-404e-bdca-676545412ee8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory appears empty. Let me check if there are any files at all, and also search for any relevant .NET or Kubernetes configuration patterns.\n\nSince there's no repository content to work with, I'll provide the user with the configuration they need based on my knowledge of .NET NativeAOT crash dump collection with `createdump` in Kubernetes.\n\nFor NativeAOT .NET apps, crash dump collection works differently than CoreCLR. Key points:\n\n1. **NativeAOT and createdump**: In NativeAOT, the runtime doesn't automatically invoke `createdump` on crash like CoreCLR does. You need to configure environment variables to enable this.\n\n\n2. **Environment variables for crash dumps**: I need to set variables like `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` to enable dump generation, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` to specify the dump type, and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` for the output path, but I'm realizing the configuration differs for NativeAOT compared to standard CoreCLR.\n\nFor NativeAOT in .NET 8+, the `createdump` tool handles crash dumps, and I'd use the same environment variables but need to be careful about how the tool is invoked since it's not bundled the same way with the NativeAOT runtime.\n\nIn Kubernetes, I'd need to set up an `emptyDir` volume for storing the dumps, configure ulimits for core dump size through a security context, potentially adjust `/proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern`, and ensure the pod has the right ptrace capabilities to actually capture the dumps.","outputTokens":1349,"requestId":"418B:21AE1A:61549E3:6A95391:69F16380"},"id":"18274f53-d42e-4a8f-9ef3-295030898f90","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:49:15.900Z","parentId":"2c567394-2146-425b-9cd5-4082c577618f"}
